      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the memory usage issue is a classic case of a memory leak, and it seems like the buffer allocated in each iteration of the loop is not being deallocated. The `new` operator is used to allocate memory, but we must use `delete` to free it when we're done with it. In your code, the `buffer` is not being deleted, which means the memory is not being returned to the system after it's no longer needed. This is likely the cause of the increasing memory usage with each loop iteration.\n\nTo fix this, you should add `delete[] buffer;` at the end of the loop, right after the `perform_validation(buffer);` call. This will ensure that the memory allocated for each buffer is properly released, preventing the memory leak. Here's the corrected code snippet:\n\n```cpp\nvoid process_transactions(Transaction* incoming) {\n    for (int i = 0; i < incoming->count; ++i) {\n        // allocate temporary buffer for processing\n        char* buffer = new char[256]; \n        \n        // ... some logic to copy data into buffer ...\n        strncpy(buffer, incoming->data[i].raw_payload, 255);\n        \n        perform_validation(buffer);\n        \n        // we need this buffer",
